# editor.conf - Editor shortcuts for opening files/folders
# Format: editor_name|command|description
#
# Fields (pipe-separated):
#   1. Function name (used with: kit <name> <file/folder>)
#   2. Full command to open the editor
#   3. Description
#
# Note: After adding editors to your editor.conf, reload with:
#       source $KIT_EXT_DIR/loader.zsh
#
# ============================================================================
# PLATFORM DIFFERENCES
# ============================================================================
#
# macOS GUI Apps:
#   Use: open -a "AppName"
#   Example: zed|open -a Zed|Zed editor
#
# macOS Terminal Editors & Linux:
#   Use: the command directly (must be in PATH)
#   Example: code|code|VS Code
#   Example: nvim|nvim|Neovim
#
# Linux GUI Apps:
#   Use: the command directly (must be in PATH)
#   Example: code|code|VS Code
#   Example: subl|subl|Sublime Text
#
# ============================================================================
# EXAMPLES
# ============================================================================
#
# Usage:
#   kit code myfile.md      # Opens myfile.md in VS Code
#   kit zed .               # Opens current folder in Zed
#   kit nvim config.yaml    # Opens config.yaml in Neovim
#
# ============================================================================

# Popular cross-platform editors (work on both macOS and Linux)
code|code|VS Code
cursor|cursor|Cursor AI editor
subl|subl|Sublime Text

# macOS-specific GUI apps (use 'open -a' for GUI applications)
zed|open -a Zed|Zed editor (macOS)

# Terminal-based editors (work on both macOS and Linux)
nvim|nvim|Neovim
vim|vim|Vim
hx|hx|Helix editor
emacs|emacs|GNU Emacs

# JetBrains IDEs
idea|idea|IntelliJ IDEA
webstorm|webstorm|WebStorm
pycharm|pycharm|PyCharm
rider|rider|Rider

# Other editors
nano|nano|Nano editor
micro|micro|Micro editor
